Now, Sir, a few words with regard to my hon. friend from West Durham (Mr. Blake) and the criticisms made by that hon. gentleman upon the remarks I had made just before he spoke. I may say that I spoke without due preparation : I had only the time between ten o’clock in the morning. 1 and three in the afternoon to prepare my brief, and in the haste of preparation I probably did fall into \ some inaccuracy, and a1 nongstthesei naccuracies was one, technical rather in its character, with regard to the course adopted by the United States Hover-w ment when Louisiana was purchased in 1803. I stated that the United States Government, from the inception, had sought by every means to secure a single language, and had abolished the use of the French. But I find that for the first few years ‘ that policy was not so rigorously enforced as later on, and the use of French was permitted, to a :limited extent, and in that sense my hon. friend had me at a disadvantage ; for I had gone upon the assumption that the well understood general policy of the Government had been more vigorously enforced than probably was the case at the outset.
